defaultOnce incorporated into soil the material is effectively immobilised.  In some situations a fraction of the small char particles may be transported by water. Those particles will be deposited somewhere, often in deep-s
defaultea sediment.  These natural processes occur already.  Forest fires have put char pieces and particles onto and into the world’s soils for the past 500 million years.
defaultProduction of biochar needs to be done in properly-designed kilns that avoid the release o
defaultf gaseous pollutants.  Registration of schemes for market access
default offers a means of control.
defaultThe IBI and other organisations have drawn up and published quality standards for biochar that specify maximum safe limits for potential soil contaminants such as h
defaulteavy metals, polycyclic aromatics and dioxins.
defaultBiochar is s
defaulthowing promise as a component of horticultural growing media that 
defaultcould substantially reduce
default the damaging extraction of peat
default from environmentally-sensitive areas.
default  There is a large market for such products in the UK.
defaultBiochar may be effective as a delivery 
defaultmedium for chemical fertilizers and as a means of controlling the rate of release of nutrients to crops.
